Seven suspects were killed by police on Friday night during a shootout following a manhunt after the murders of five police officers and a civilian at the Ngcobo Police Station on Wednesday. Hawks spokesperson Brigadier Hangwani Mulaudzi said the suspects had been killed after a multidisciplinary team had located them in a church which the gang were using as a hideout. 

Another 10 suspects were arrested, while an unknown number escaped. One police officer was injured and is recovering in hospital. “The task team which comprises of the Hawks, Detectives, Crime Intelligence, the Task Force, National Intervention Unit and the Tactical Response Team followed information on Friday evening of a possible gang that was responsible for the tragic incident,” Mulaudzi said in a statement. “The group which uses a church as a hiding place was cornered inside the church premises.  A gun battle between suspects and police ensued which left seven suspects dead and a task force member injured in the legs.” The team made the major breakthrough late on Friday, several people had been taken in for questioning in the wake of the killings but police said they had not been arrested. Police Minister Fikile Mbalula visited the area and the families of the victims of the police killings promising swift action. According to the police, the police officers and a civilian were killed on Wednesday morning when the station was attacked without warning and the police were randomly fired upon. Three were killed at the community service centre and an – the off-duty soldier was shot dead as the assailants were fleeing.
The men then made off with a police van with two officers inside it. These men were then found shot dead execution-style six kilometres from the station.